Q.  How does the gameplay work?

A.  Like in most fighting games, it is a tournament format where a player
fights one of the other characters which is being played by either the
computer or another human player.   Each fighter has special moves specific
to him/her in addition to basic moves that all characters can do.  The
"life gauge" is a large samurai sword upon which blood accumulates the more
the character is hit.  Blood periodically drips to the floor and stays
there throughout the round.  Needless to say, all blows by an opponent
cause massive amounts of blood to fly.  The game begins in a labyrinth
(with full 360 degree control and floors and ceilings) where each player
selects their fighter.  In a one player game the player also chooses his
opponent at this point.  During this whole process there is great music
playing.  Once both characters are selected, a door opens and players can
run down the hall to their fighting area.  The background for the battle is
determined by who is the second player.  Ted Taquechi has said the maze
part of the game will play a larger role in the game.  You will receive
keys for each opponent you defeat.  Also, your character will gain some of
your opponents powers after you defeat them.   Having all of the keys will
allow you exit the labyrinth... provided you can find it (and defeat the
Master Boss).

NOTE: While in "blood/gore" mode, blood does not disappear five seconds
after it hits the ground as in MK... it stays there until at least the end
of the round, staining the floor.  This may or may not change in the final
version.  Also, there is a "secret" TURBO MODE that will run at 60 frames
per second for faster/smoother action!  As I understand it this TURBO MODE
was not shown at the SCES.  The version shown on 6/25-26 at the Summer
Consumer Electronics show was v .32 so it's still early.
